INSERT INTO `activities` VALUES (282,'Evaluate Your Leadership Presence','','Look for opportunities when you have a chance to practice your leadership presence, and have time to reflect after. When you are ready to do so, make contact with someone who will be part of the event (say, a presentation to an executive group, or facilitating a community of practice event). Tell them that youd like them to act as a friendly observer of your presence, and that youd like their feedback after the event. <p><p>After, have a conversation with your friendly observer. What did they notice? Are your efforts succeeding? What do you want to change? What aspect of your presence do you need to focus on next? Make note, and track your progress in whatever way makes sense to you. Some people might record their reflections on video or voice, some might keep a notebook--do what works for you, but be sure to come back to your reflections to plan for your next opportunity to practice. ','','','',2,NULL,NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,0,NULL,1,'2020-06-29 23:07:25',1,'2020-06-29 23:08:33',1,4,'1 hr or less',NULL);
INSERT INTO `activities` VALUES (283,'Truth and Reconciliation Commission (TRC) Calls to Action','http://trc.ca/assets/pdf/Calls_to_Action_English2.pdf','In June 2015, the Truth and Reconciliation Commission (TRC) released 10 principles of reconciliation and 94 calls to action that lead to a path of reconciliation. In December 2015, Prime Minister Trudeau accepted all 94 calls and committed that the federal government would, in partnership with Indigenous communities, the provinces, territories, and other vital partners, fully implement the TRC Calls to Action, starting with the implementation of the United Nations Declaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples (UNDRIP). The first principle of reconciliation confirms that UNDRIP is the framework for reconciliation for all sectors of Canadian society.<p><p> <b>Call to action #57: Professional Development and Training for Public Servants</b><p><p>"We call upon federal, provincial, territorial, and municipal governments to provide education to public servants on the history of Aboriginal peoples, including the history and legacy of residential schools, the United Nations Declaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples, Treaties and Aboriginal rights, Indigenous law, and Aboriginal-Crown relations. This will require skills-based training in intercultural competency, conflict resolution, human rights, and anti-racism." <p><p>The link provided is for the full text of the Calls to Action.','','','',2,NULL,NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,15,NULL,1,'2020-06-30 23:11:07',1,'2021-02-11 17:03:18',1,2,'Under 10 mins','TRCC2A');
INSERT INTO `activities` VALUES (284,'United Nations Declaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples (UNDRIP)','http://www.un.org/esa/socdev/unpfii/documents/DRIPS_en.pdf','One function of government is to uphold the rights described in the UNDRIP. This document that describes both individual and collective rights of Indigenous peoples around the world. It offers guidance on cooperative relationships with Indigenous peoples to states, the United Nations, and other international organizations based on the principles of equality, partnership, good faith and mutual respect. It addresses the rights of Indigenous peoples on issues such as:<ol><li>culture</li><li>identity</li><li>religion</li><li>language</li><li>health</li><li>education</li> <li>community</li></ol>The declaration was adopted by resolution of the United Nations General Assembly on September 13, 2007. The 10 principles of UNDRIP serve as guides to assist in repairing the damaged relationship between the Indigenous and non-Indigenous peoples of Canada. <p><p> Link provided is for the full document.','','','',2,NULL,NULL,0,0,NULL,NULL,0,22,NULL,1,'2020-06-30 23:21:45',1,'2021-02-11 17:03:25',1,2,'',NULL);
